  <h2>Collections</h2>

  <h3>Baha'i Faith</h3>
  <p>
    The most comprehensive collection in the library at 5,540 documents, spanning the writings of
    the Bab, Baha'u'llah, 'Abdu'l-Baha, Shoghi Effendi, and the Universal House of Justice.
  </p>

  <h4>Core Publications</h4>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>The Hidden Words</strong> — Baha'u'llah's ethical and spiritual guidance</li>
    <li><strong>The Kitab-i-Iqan</strong> — Book of Certitude, on progressive revelation</li>
    <li><strong>Gleanings from the Writings of Baha'u'llah</strong> — Key passages compiled by Shoghi Effendi</li>
    <li><strong>Some Answered Questions</strong> — 'Abdu'l-Baha's answers to philosophical inquiries</li>
    <li><strong>Paris Talks</strong> — Addresses given by 'Abdu'l-Baha during his Western travels</li>
  </ul>

  <h4>Pilgrim Notes</h4>
  <p>
    A unique collection of first-hand accounts from pilgrims who visited 'Abdu'l-Baha and
    Shoghi Effendi. These notes capture intimate conversations and teachings not found elsewhere.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Over 200 pilgrim accounts spanning 1898–1957</li>
    <li>Multiple visits from key figures like May Maxwell, Lua Getsinger, and Roy Wilhelm</li>
    <li>Valuable historical context and personal observations</li>
  </ul>

  <h4>Letters and Tablets</h4>
  <ul>
    <li>Tablets of Baha'u'llah revealed after the Kitab-i-Aqdas</li>
    <li>Selections from the Writings of 'Abdu'l-Baha</li>
    <li>Letters of Shoghi Effendi to individual believers and communities</li>
    <li>Messages of the Universal House of Justice</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Islam — 293 Documents, 1.54 Million Passages</h3>
  <p>
    One of the most comprehensive digital Islamic text collections available for semantic search —
    293 documents yielding over 1.54 million passages, primarily in classical Arabic. An English
    query for "the nature of God's mercy" surfaces relevant Arabic passages; Arabic queries find
    English results. This cross-language capability operates on meaning, not translation, powered
    by 3072-dimensional multilingual embeddings.
  </p>
  <p>
    The collection spans every major discipline of traditional Islamic scholarship: hadith, tafsir,
    fiqh, kalam, tasawwuf, falsafa, sirah, and more — representing Sunni, Shi'ah, and Sufi
    traditions in depth.
  </p>

  <h4>Traditions (Hadith) — 77 documents, 477,604 passages</h4>
  <p>
    The most comprehensive hadith collection available digitally in Arabic — all six canonical
    Sunni collections, the major Shi'ah collections, and the critical apparatus of hadith science.
  </p>
  <dl>
    <dt>The Six Canonical Collections (al-Kutub al-Sittah)</dt>
    <dd>Sahih al-Bukhari, Sahih Muslim, Sunan al-Tirmidhi, Sunan Abu Dawud, Sunan al-Nasai, Sunan Ibn Majah — the authoritative core of Sunni hadith literature.</dd>
    <dt>Major Supplementary Collections</dt>
    <dd>Musnad Ahmad ibn Hanbal, Muwatta Malik, Sahih Ibn Hibban, Sahih Ibn Khuzaymah, Sunan al-Daraqutni, Sunan al-Darimi, Sunan al-Bayhaqi.</dd>
    <dt>Shi'ah Canonical Collections (al-Kutub al-Arba'ah)</dt>
    <dd>al-Kafi (al-Kulayni), Man la Yahduruh al-Faqih (al-Saduq), Tahdhib al-Ahkam and al-Istibsar (al-Tusi) — plus Bihar al-Anwar (al-Majlisi), the monumental 110-volume encyclopedia of Shi'ah traditions.</dd>
    <dt>Hadith Sciences</dt>
    <dd>Works by Ibn al-Salah, Ibn Hajar, al-Suyuti, and al-Mizzi on authentication, classification, and the science of narrators (rijal).</dd>
  </dl>

  <h4>Foundational Texts (Qur'an &amp; Tafsir) — 53 documents, 370,157 passages</h4>
  <p>
    The Qur'an in multiple Arabic editions alongside the classical tradition of Qur'anic commentary
    — over 40 tafsir works spanning Sunni, Shi'ah, and Sufi interpretive traditions.
  </p>
  <dl>
    <dt>The Qur'an</dt>
    <dd>Arabic text (multiple editions) plus major English translations: Pickthall, Yusuf Ali, Arberry, Sale, and Rodwell.</dd>
    <dt>Classical Sunni Tafsir</dt>
    <dd>Tabari's Jami al-Bayan (the foundational commentary), Ibn Kathir's Tafsir, al-Qurtubi's al-Jami li-Ahkam al-Quran, Fakhr al-Din al-Razi's Mafatih al-Ghayb (the "Great Commentary"), al-Zamakhshari's al-Kashshaf.</dd>
    <dt>Shi'ah Tafsir</dt>
    <dd>al-Mizan (Tabatabai), Tafsir al-Qummi, Tafsir al-Safi (al-Kashani), Nur al-Thaqalayn, Majma al-Bayan (al-Tabarsi).</dd>
    <dt>Qur'anic Sciences</dt>
    <dd>al-Itqan fi Ulum al-Quran (al-Suyuti), al-Burhan fi Ulum al-Quran (al-Zarkashi), al-Nashr fi al-Qiraat al-Ashr (Ibn al-Jazari).</dd>
  </dl>

  <h4>Jurisprudence (Fiqh) — 39 documents, 321,726 passages</h4>
  <p>
    All four Sunni schools of law plus Ja'fari (Shi'ah) fiqh, represented by their foundational
    texts — along with works of legal theory (usul al-fiqh).
  </p>
  <dl>
    <dt>Hanafi</dt>
    <dd>al-Mabsut (al-Sarakhsi), Bada'i al-Sana'i (al-Kasani), al-Hidaya (al-Marghinani).</dd>
    <dt>Maliki</dt>
    <dd>al-Mudawwana (Sahnun), Mukhtasar Khalil, Bidayat al-Mujtahid (Ibn Rushd).</dd>
    <dt>Shafi'i</dt>
    <dd>al-Muhadhdhab (al-Shirazi), Rawdat al-Talibin (al-Nawawi), al-Umm (al-Shafi'i).</dd>
    <dt>Hanbali</dt>
    <dd>al-Mughni (Ibn Qudamah), al-Furu (Ibn Muflih).</dd>
    <dt>Ja'fari (Shi'ah)</dt>
    <dd>Jawahir al-Kalam (al-Najafi), al-Nihaya (al-Tusi), Shara'i al-Islam (al-Hilli).</dd>
    <dt>Legal Theory (Usul al-Fiqh)</dt>
    <dd>al-Muwafaqat (al-Shatibi), Kashf al-Asrar (al-Bazdawi).</dd>
  </dl>

  <h4>History &amp; Biography — 32 documents, 242,656 passages</h4>
  <p>
    From the earliest Prophetic biography through the great medieval historians and the monumental
    biographical dictionaries of Islamic civilization.
  </p>
  <dl>
    <dt>Prophetic Biography (Sirah)</dt>
    <dd>Ibn Ishaq/Ibn Hisham's al-Sirah al-Nabawiyyah, al-Waqidi's al-Maghazi, al-Tabari's Tarikh.</dd>
    <dt>Major Histories</dt>
    <dd>Tarikh al-Tabari, al-Bidaya wa'l-Nihaya (Ibn Kathir), Muqaddimah (Ibn Khaldun — the foundational work of social science), Muruj al-Dhahab (al-Mas'udi).</dd>
    <dt>Biographical Dictionaries</dt>
    <dd>Usd al-Ghaba (Ibn al-Athir), al-Isti'ab (Ibn Abd al-Barr), al-Isaba (Ibn Hajar), Tabaqat Ibn Sa'd, Wafayat al-A'yan (Ibn Khallikan), Tarikh Baghdad (al-Khatib al-Baghdadi), Tarikh Dimashq (Ibn Asakir), and Siyar al-A'lam al-Nubala (al-Dhahabi) — the monumental biographical encyclopedia of 300+ volumes.</dd>
  </dl>

  <h4>Mysticism (Tasawwuf) — 21 documents, 65,976 passages</h4>
  <p>
    A stunning collection of Sufi classics in both Arabic and Persian — from the systematic
    treatises of the masters to the soaring poetry of Rumi and Ibn al-Farid.
  </p>
  <dl>
    <dt>Ibn Arabi</dt>
    <dd>Fusus al-Hikam, al-Futuhat al-Makkiyya, Diwan — the summit of Islamic metaphysical mysticism.</dd>
    <dt>Rumi</dt>
    <dd>Masnavi (Persian) and Divan-e Shams (Persian) — among the most widely read mystical poetry in any language.</dd>
    <dt>al-Ghazali</dt>
    <dd>Ihya Ulum al-Din (the "Revival of Religious Sciences" — his magnum opus), Mishkat al-Anwar, al-Munqidh min al-Dalal.</dd>
    <dt>Other Masters</dt>
    <dd>al-Qushayri's Risala fi Ilm al-Tasawwuf, al-Hujwiri's Kashf al-Mahjub (Persian — the oldest Persian Sufi treatise), Abd al-Qadir al-Jilani's Futuh al-Ghayb.</dd>
    <dt>Poetry</dt>
    <dd>Ibn al-Farid's Diwan, al-Busiri's al-Burdah (the beloved ode to the Prophet), Attar's Tadhkirat al-Awliya.</dd>
  </dl>

  <h4>Philosophy (Falsafa) — 21 documents, 24,714 passages</h4>
  <p>
    The full arc of Islamic philosophy — from the Greek-inspired founders to the Andalusian
    synthesizers to the later Illuminationist and transcendent wisdom traditions.
  </p>
  <dl>
    <dt>The Founders</dt>
    <dd>al-Kindi (the "Philosopher of the Arabs"), al-Farabi — al-Madina al-Fadila (The Virtuous City), Ihsa al-Ulum (Enumeration of the Sciences).</dd>
    <dt>The Pinnacle: Ibn Sina (Avicenna)</dt>
    <dd>al-Shifa (The Book of Healing — his encyclopedic masterwork), al-Isharat wa al-Tanbihat (Remarks and Admonitions).</dd>
    <dt>The Andalusians</dt>
    <dd>Ibn Rushd (Averroes) — Tahafut al-Tahafut and Fasl al-Maqal; Ibn Tufayl's Hayy ibn Yaqzan (the philosophical novel that influenced Locke and Defoe).</dd>
    <dt>The Great Debate</dt>
    <dd>al-Ghazali's Tahafut al-Falasifa (The Incoherence of the Philosophers) paired with Ibn Rushd's Tahafut al-Tahafut (The Incoherence of the Incoherence) — one of history's great intellectual exchanges.</dd>
    <dt>Later Tradition</dt>
    <dd>Mulla Sadra's al-Asfar al-Arba'a (transcendent wisdom), Nasir al-Din al-Tusi, Miskawayh.</dd>
    <dt>Encyclopedic</dt>
    <dd>Rasa'il Ikhwan al-Safa — the 52-volume Epistles of the Brethren of Purity.</dd>
  </dl>

  <h4>Shi'ah Imams — 19 documents, 14,546 passages</h4>
  <p>
    Prayers, sermons, letters, and teachings attributed to the Twelve Imams — the spiritual
    and intellectual successors recognized in Shi'ah Islam.
  </p>
  <dl>
    <dt>Imam Ali ibn Abi Talib</dt>
    <dd>Nahj al-Balagha (Peak of Eloquence — sermons, letters, and sayings) and Ghurar al-Hikam (Exalted Aphorisms). Includes translations by Khazeh Fananapazir.</dd>
    <dt>Imam Zayn al-Abidin</dt>
    <dd>al-Sahifa al-Sajjadiyya (the "Psalms of Islam") — a devotional prayer collection of remarkable beauty.</dd>
    <dt>Other Imams</dt>
    <dd>Teachings of Imam Ja'far al-Sadiq, Imam al-Baqir, and Imam al-Hadi.</dd>
    <dt>Commemorative Works</dt>
    <dd>Maqtal al-Husayn (Abu Mikhnaf), al-Luhuf (Ibn Tawus) — on the tragedy of Karbala.</dd>
  </dl>

  <h4>Doctrine &amp; Theology (Kalam) — 17 documents, 9,529 passages</h4>
  <p>
    The systematic theological tradition of Islam — Sunni, Shi'ah, and the heresiographical
    literature that maps the full landscape of Islamic thought.
  </p>
  <dl>
    <dt>Sunni Theology</dt>
    <dd>al-Ashari — al-Ibanah and Maqalat al-Islamiyyin; al-Maturidi; al-Tahawi's al-Aqidah (the most widely studied creedal text); al-Baqillani; Ibn Taymiyyah.</dd>
    <dt>Shi'ah Theology</dt>
    <dd>al-Mufid — Awa'il al-Maqalat; al-Saduq — al-Itiqadat; al-Murtada — al-Shafi fi al-Imamah.</dd>
    <dt>Heresiography</dt>
    <dd>al-Shahrastani's al-Milal wa al-Nihal and al-Baghdadi's al-Farq bayn al-Firaq — encyclopedic surveys of Islamic sects and world religions.</dd>
  </dl>

  <h4>Miscellaneous — 5 documents</h4>
  <p>
    Literary classics of Arabic letters: al-Maqamat (al-Hariri and al-Hamadhani — the pinnacle
    of Arabic rhymed prose), Aja'ib al-Makhluqat (al-Qazwini's cosmography), and Kitab al-Aghani
    (Abu al-Faraj al-Isfahani's monumental anthology of Arabic poetry and song).
  </p>

  <h3>Other Traditions</h3>
  <p>
    We are actively expanding the library beyond its current collections. The Islamic and Baha'i
    holdings represent years of careful curation — we intend to bring the same depth to other
    traditions rather than add texts piecemeal.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Buddhism</strong> — Coming soon. We currently have one Buddhist text. A proper collection will include the Pali canon, Mahayana sutras, Tibetan commentaries, and Zen literature.</li>
    <li><strong>Christianity</strong> — Coming soon. Planned coverage of patristic literature, medieval scholastics, mystical tradition, and Reformation texts.</li>
    <li><strong>Hinduism</strong> — Coming soon. The Vedas, Upanishads, Bhagavad Gita, and classical darshana literature.</li>
    <li><strong>Judaism</strong> — Coming soon. Torah, Talmud, midrash, medieval philosophy (Maimonides, Judah Halevi), and Kabbalah.</li>
    <li><strong>Other traditions</strong> — Sikhism, Taoism, Zoroastrianism, and others are on the roadmap.</li>
  </ul>

